(2493, 1745, 'A managed switch is a type of network switch that provides administrators with greater control and configurability over their network compared to unmanaged switches. Here are the key characteristics and features of managed switches:\nRemote Management, \nVLAN Support, \nQuality of Service (QoS), \nSecurity Features, \nMonitoring and Troubleshooting, \nPort Mirroring, \nRedundancy and Link Aggregation, \nFirmware Updates, \nTraffic Management, \nAdvanced Routing', 3, '2023-09-13 20:39:08', 1),
(2494, 1746, 'is a basic type of network switch that operates at the data link layer (Layer 2) of the OSI model. It is designed to be plug-and-play, meaning it requires little to no configuration and is easy to set up. Here are the key characteristics and features of unmanaged switches:\nSimplicity \nNo Management Interface \nBasic Switching \nNo VLAN Support:  \nNo Quality of Service (QoS): \nNo Advanced Features:\nCost-Effective\nLimited Troubleshooting\nNo Remote Configuration', 3, '2023-09-13 20:39:08', 1),
